attributes.magic: ELF 64-bit LSB executable, x86-64, version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, stripped

sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects programs that connect to uncommon destination ports

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This binary is a highly sophisticated, modular Linux implant identified as 'VoidLink Implant Core v3.0'. It functions as a Command and Control (C2) agent with extensive capabilities for persistence, stealth, and exfiltration. Key malicious behaviors include encrypted beaconing to a hardcoded C2 (8.149.128.10), automated credential harvesting (SSH, AWS, and Kubernetes configs), and the deployment of both Linux Kernel Modules (LKM) and eBPF programs to hide files, processes, and network connections. The binary also contains logic to disable shell history (HISTFILE=/dev/null) and can compile rootkit components on the target system by attempting to install build dependencies like clang, llvm, and kernel headers.
